-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- JOHN CHAPTER 16 — The Spirit's Work, Sorrow into Joy, Victory over the World
-- 33 verses · Greek text · Word studies · Cross-refs
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════

-- Step 1: Insert chapter metadata
INSERT INTO chapters (book_id, chapter_number, overview, theme, key_word_original, key_word_meaning, outline)
SELECT b.id, 16,
  'John 16 continues and concludes the Upper Room Discourse before the High Priestly Prayer of chapter 17. Jesus begins by explaining why he has told the disciples about the world''s hatred (15:18-25): so that they would not stumble when persecution comes (v.1). He predicts that they will be expelled from synagogues and even killed by those who think they are serving God (vv.1-4). He explains that his departure is to their advantage because only through his departure can the Paraclete come (v.7). The Spirit''s ministry is then described in the most extensive pneumatological passage in the Upper Room Discourse: he will ''reprove the world of sin, and of righteousness, and of judgment'' (v.8) — three aspects of the Spirit''s convicting work. ''Of sin, because they believe not on me; of righteousness, because I go to my Father; of judgment, because the prince of this world is judged'' (vv.9-11). Jesus then speaks of the Spirit of truth who ''will guide you into all truth'' (v.13) and will ''shew you things to come'' (v.13). The Spirit glorifies Christ by taking what is Christ''s and declaring it to the disciples (vv.14-15). The disciples are puzzled by the ''little while'' sayings (vv.16-19). Jesus explains with the parable of the woman in childbirth: present sorrow will become irreplaceable joy — a joy that no one will take from them (vv.20-22). He promises that prayer in his name will be answered by the Father directly — no longer through an intermediary (vv.23-27). The disciples confess their belief, but Jesus warns that they will scatter, leaving him alone — yet he is never alone because the Father is with him (vv.28-32). The chapter closes with the most triumphant verse in the Discourse: ''In the world ye shall have tribulation: but be of good cheer; I have overcome the world'' (v.33).',
  'The Spirit Convicts, Guides, and Glorifies — Be of Good Cheer',
  'ἐλέγχω (elegchō)',
  'To convict, convince, rebuke, expose — from elegchos (proof, conviction). The Spirit''s work toward the world is elegchō: he makes the case, presses the argument, brings to light what is hidden. In legal usage, elegchō is to cross-examine and refute; in moral usage, to convict of wrongdoing and bring to shame. The three dimensions of v.8 — sin, righteousness, judgment — are three courtroom verdicts the Spirit brings: (1) the world is guilty of the sin of unbelief; (2) Christ is vindicated as righteous by his resurrection/exaltation; (3) the prince of this world stands condemned. This work happens through the preaching of the gospel; the Spirit uses the proclaimed word to produce conviction leading to repentance (Acts 2:37: ''they were pricked in their heart'').',
  '["Warning About Persecution (vv.1-4): These things have I spoken unto you that ye should not be offended. They shall put you out of the synagogues yea the time cometh that whosoever killeth you will think that he doeth God service. And these things will they do unto you because they have not known the Father nor me. But these things have I told you that when the time shall come ye may remember that I told you of them","The Spirit''s Coming (vv.5-11): But now I go my way to him that sent me and none of you asketh me Whither goest thou? But because I have said these things unto you sorrow hath filled your heart. Nevertheless I tell you the truth It is expedient for you that I go away for if I go not away the Comforter will not come unto you but if I depart I will send him unto you. And when he is come he will reprove the world of sin and of righteousness and of judgment of sin because they believe not on me of righteousness because I go to my Father and ye see me no more of judgment because the prince of this world is judged","The Spirit Guides into All Truth (vv.12-15): I have yet many things to say unto you but ye cannot bear them now. Howbeit when he the Spirit of truth is come he will guide you into all truth for he shall not speak of himself but whatsoever he shall hear that shall he speak and he will shew you things to come. He shall glorify me for he shall receive of mine and shall shew it unto you. All things that the Father hath are mine therefore said I that he shall take of mine and shall shew it unto you","Sorrow Turned to Joy (vv.16-24): A little while and ye shall not see me and again a little while and ye shall see me because I go to the Father. Then said some of his disciples among themselves What is this that he saith unto us A little while and ye shall not see me and again a little while and ye shall see me? Jesus knew that they were desirous to ask him and said unto them Do ye enquire among yourselves of that I said A little while and ye shall not see me and again a little while and ye shall see me? Verily verily I say unto you That ye shall weep and lament but the world shall rejoice and ye shall be sorrowful but your sorrow shall be turned into joy. A woman when she is in travail hath sorrow because her hour is come but as soon as she is delivered of the child she remembereth no more the anguish for joy that a man is born into the world. And ye now therefore have sorrow but I will see you again and your heart shall rejoice and your joy no man taketh from you. And in that day ye shall ask me nothing. Verily verily I say unto you Whatsoever ye shall ask the Father in my name he will give it you. Hitherto have ye asked nothing in my name ask and ye shall receive that your joy may be full","The Father''s Love (vv.25-28): These things have I spoken unto you in proverbs but the time cometh when I shall no more speak unto you in proverbs but I shall shew you plainly of the Father. At that day ye shall ask in my name and I say not unto you that I will pray the Father for you for the Father himself loveth you because ye have loved me and have believed that I came out from God. I came forth from the Father and am come into the world again I leave the world and go to the Father","Victory over the World (vv.29-33): His disciples said unto him Lo now speakest thou plainly and speakest no proverb. Now are we sure that thou knowest all things and needest not that any man should ask thee by this we believe that thou camest forth from God. Jesus answered them Do ye now believe? Behold the hour cometh yea is now come that ye shall be scattered every man to his own and shall leave me alone and yet I am not alone because the Father is with me. These things I have spoken unto you that in me ye might have peace. In the world ye shall have tribulation but be of good cheer I have overcome the world"]'
FROM books b WHERE b.name = 'John';

-- Step 2: Insert all 33 verses
INSERT INTO verses (chapter_id, verse_number, kjv_text, original_text, transliteration, study_note, doctrinal_note)
SELECT c.id, v.verse_number, v.kjv_text, v.original_text, v.transliteration, v.study_note, v.doctrinal_note
FROM chapters c
JOIN books b ON c.book_id = b.id
CROSS JOIN (VALUES
  (1, 'These things have I spoken unto you, that ye should not be offended.',
   'Ταῦτα λελάληκα ὑμῖν ἵνα μὴ σκανδαλισθῆτε',
   'Tauta lelalēka hymin hina mē skandalisthēte',
   '''That ye should not be offended'' (hina mē skandalisthēte — so that you may not be caused to stumble; skandalizō: to cause to fall, to be a stumbling block). ''Skandalon'' (stumbling block, trap) gives us ''scandal.'' Jesus''s purpose in foretelling persecution is prophylactic: when it comes, they will remember and stand firm rather than be caught off guard and fall away. The teaching serves as an inoculation against faith-destroying shock.',
   NULL),
  (2, 'They shall put you out of the synagogues: yea, the time cometh, that whosoever killeth you will think that he doeth God service.',
   'ἀποσυναγώγους ποιήσουσιν ὑμᾶς ἀλλ᾽ ἔρχεται ὥρα ἵνα πᾶς ὁ ἀποκτείνας ὑμᾶς δόξῃ λατρείαν προσφέρειν τῷ θεῷ',
   'aposynagōgous poiēsousin hymas all erchetai hōra hina pas ho apokteinōn hymas doxē latreian prospherein tō theō',
   '''Whosoever killeth you will think that he doeth God service'' (ho apokteinōn hymas doxē latreian prospherein tō theō — the one killing you will suppose he is offering a service/act of worship to God; latreian: religious service, worship). This was the mentality of the early persecutors — Saul of Tarsus believed he was serving God by destroying the church (Acts 8:1-3; 26:9-11; Philippians 3:6). Religious sincerity without truth is the most dangerous combination. The Pharisees'' framework defined blasphemy as a capital offence deserving death (Leviticus 24:16); by their definition, Jesus and his followers were blasphemers to be eliminated.',
   NULL),
  (3, 'And these things will they do unto you, because they have not known the Father, nor me.',
   'καὶ ταῦτα ποιήσουσιν ὅτι οὐκ ἔγνωσαν τὸν πατέρα οὐδὲ ἐμέ',
   'kai tauta poiēsousin hoti ouk egnōsan ton patera oude eme',
   'The root of religious persecution is theological ignorance: ''they have not known the Father, nor me.'' True knowledge of God produces mercy, not murder; compassion, not condemnation. The persecutors do not lack religious knowledge — they have centuries of Torah study — but they lack the knowledge of God that only comes through the Son (14:6-9). This is the same diagnosis as 15:21. Zeal without knowledge is dangerous (Romans 10:2).',
   NULL),
  (4, 'But these things have I told you, that when the time shall come, ye may remember that I told you of them. And these things I said not unto you at the beginning, because I was with you.',
   'ἀλλὰ ταῦτα λελάληκα ὑμῖν ἵνα ὅταν ἔλθῃ ἡ ὥρα αὐτῶν μνημονεύητε αὐτῶν ὅτι ἐγὼ εἶπον ὑμῖν ταῦτα δὲ ὑμῖν ἐξ ἀρχῆς οὐκ εἶπον ὅτι μεθ᾽ ὑμῶν ἤμην',
   'alla tauta lelalēka hymin hina hotan elthē hē hōra autōn mnēmoneuēte autōn hoti egō eipon hymin tauta de hymin ex archēs ouk eipon hoti meth hymōn ēmēn',
   '''Because I was with you'' (hoti meth hymōn ēmēn — because I was with you). While Jesus was physically present, his presence was their protection; the authorities focused their opposition on him rather than the disciples. Now that he is leaving, they need to be forewarned. The warnings of persecution were not given earlier because they were not yet needed — timing in teaching is as important as content.',
   NULL),
  (5, 'But now I go my way to him that sent me; and none of you asketh me, Whither goest thou?',
   'νῦν δὲ ὑπάγω πρὸς τὸν πέμψαντά με καὶ οὐδεὶς ἐξ ὑμῶν ἐρωτᾷ με Ποῦ ὑπάγεις',
   'nyn de hypagō pros ton pempsanta me kai oudeis ex hymōn erōtā me Pou hypageis',
   '''None of you asketh me, Whither goest thou?'' Thomas asked this in 14:5 and Peter in 13:36, but those questions were self-centred (what about us?). Now, absorbed in their own sorrow (v.6), they have stopped asking about his destination. Jesus is gently pointing to their inward focus: they are grieving about themselves rather than rejoicing for him (cf. 14:28: ''If ye loved me, ye would rejoice, because I said, I go unto the Father'').',
   NULL),
  (6, 'But because I have said these things unto you, sorrow hath filled your heart.',
   'ἀλλ᾽ ὅτι ταῦτα λελάληκα ὑμῖν ἡ λύπη πεπλήρωκεν ὑμῶν τὴν καρδίαν',
   'all hoti tauta lelalēka hymin hē lypē peplērōken hymōn tēn kardian',
   '''Sorrow hath filled your heart'' (hē lypē peplērōken hymōn tēn kardian — sorrow has filled your heart; perfect: has filled and remains filled). The disciples are overwhelmed with grief. They cannot see beyond the immediate loss to the gain that will follow. This is the human limitation that Jesus is about to address: sorrow is real and valid, but it is partial sight. The full picture is much better.',
   NULL),
  (7, 'Nevertheless I tell you the truth; It is expedient for you that I go away: for if I go not away, the Comforter will not come unto you; but if I depart, I will send him unto you.',
   'ἀλλ᾽ ἐγὼ τὴν ἀλήθειαν λέγω ὑμῖν συμφέρει ὑμῖν ἵνα ἐγὼ ἀπέλθω ἐὰν γὰρ μὴ ἀπέλθω ὁ παράκλητος οὐκ ἐλεύσεται πρὸς ὑμᾶς ἐὰν δὲ πορευθῶ πέμψω αὐτὸν πρὸς ὑμᾶς',
   'all egō tēn alētheian legō hymin sympherei hymin hina egō apelthō ean gar mē apelthō ho paraklētos ouk eleusetai pros hymas ean de poreuthō pempsō auton pros hymas',
   '''It is expedient for you that I go away'' (sympherei hymin hina egō apelthō — it is profitable/advantageous for you that I go away). This is a stunning claim: the disciples are better off with the Spirit than with the bodily-present Jesus. The Spirit is omnipresent (Jesus was locally present); the Spirit indwells (Jesus was externally with them); the Spirit is the agent of new birth (Jesus performed it but the Spirit effects it). The departure of the Incarnate Son is the condition for the universal presence of the Spirit.',
   NULL),
  (8, 'And when he is come, he will reprove the world of sin, and of righteousness, and of judgment:',
   'καὶ ἐλθὼν ἐκεῖνος ἐλέγξει τὸν κόσμον περὶ ἁμαρτίας καὶ περὶ δικαιοσύνης καὶ περὶ κρίσεως',
   'kai elthōn ekeinos elengxei ton kosmon peri hamartias kai peri dikaiosynēs kai peri kriseōs',
   '''He will reprove the world'' (ekeinos elengxei ton kosmon — that one will convict the world; elengchō: to convict by evidence, to expose). The Spirit''s work toward the world (through the disciples'' witness) is prosecutorial: he brings three verdicts against the world system. This is the courtroom of history: the Spirit is both witness and advocate, presenting the case against the world''s rejection of Christ. ''The world'' (ton kosmon) — the world-system organised in opposition to God.',
   NULL),
  (9, 'Of sin, because they believe not on me;',
   'περὶ ἁμαρτίας μέν ὅτι οὐ πιστεύουσιν εἰς ἐμέ',
   'peri hamartias men hoti ou pisteuousin eis eme',
   '''Of sin, because they believe not on me'' (peri hamartias hoti ou pisteuousin eis eme — concerning sin, because they do not believe into me). The supreme sin in John is not murder, adultery, or idolatry — it is unbelief in Christ. All other sins are subsumed in this fundamental refusal of the light (3:19-20). The Spirit convicts of this specific sin: not merely of moral failure but of the categorical rejection of the Son of God. This is the sin that leads to death (1 John 5:16) because it cuts off the only source of forgiveness.',
   NULL),
  (10, 'Of righteousness, because I go to my Father, and ye see me no more;',
   'περὶ δικαιοσύνης δέ ὅτι πρὸς τὸν πατέρα ὑπάγω καὶ οὐκέτι θεωρεῖτέ με',
   'peri dikaiosynēs de hoti pros ton patera hypagō kai ouketi theōreite me',
   '''Of righteousness, because I go to my Father'' (peri dikaiosynēs hoti pros ton patera hypagō). The Spirit convicts the world concerning righteousness — specifically by the fact of Jesus''s resurrection and exaltation. The world said Jesus was a blasphemer and lawbreaker; the resurrection reversed that verdict: God declared him righteous by raising him (Romans 1:4; Acts 2:32-36). The ascension to the Father is the Father''s vindication of the Son. ''Ye see me no more'' — though no longer visibly present, the Spirit testifies to his risen, vindicated status.',
   NULL),
  (11, 'Of judgment, because the prince of this world is judged.',
   'περὶ δὲ κρίσεως ὅτι ὁ ἄρχων τοῦ κόσμου τούτου κέκριται',
   'peri de kriseōs hoti ho archōn tou kosmou toutou kekritai',
   '''Because the prince of this world is judged'' (hoti ho archōn tou kosmou toutou kekritai — because the ruler of this world has been judged; perfect tense: a past act with present standing). At the cross, Satan was definitively judged and disarmed (12:31; Colossians 2:15; Hebrews 2:14). The Spirit convicts of coming judgment by pointing to the already-accomplished judgment of the world''s ruler. If the ruler is judged, all who remain in his domain face the same judgment. The cross is the anticipation and guarantee of the final judgment.',
   NULL),
  (12, 'I have yet many things to say unto you, but ye cannot bear them now.',
   'ἔτι πολλὰ ἔχω ὑμῖν λέγειν ἀλλ᾽ οὐ δύνασθε βαστάζειν ἄρτι',
   'eti polla echō hymin legein all ou dynasthe bastazein arti',
   '''Ye cannot bear them now'' (ou dynasthe bastazein arti — you are not able to carry/bear them now; bastazō: to carry a weight, to endure). The disciples are spiritually incapable of receiving more revelation in their current state — grief, confusion, immaturity. The Holy Spirit will complete the disclosure. This verse is important for understanding the relationship between Jesus''s teaching and the apostolic writings: the Spirit continued the teaching Jesus had begun, bringing deeper understanding of everything Jesus had said and done.',
   NULL),
  (13, 'Howbeit when he, the Spirit of truth, is come, he will guide you into all truth: for he shall not speak of himself; but whatsoever he shall hear, that shall he speak: and he will shew you things to come.',
   'ὅταν δὲ ἔλθῃ ἐκεῖνος τὸ πνεῦμα τῆς ἀληθείας ὁδηγήσει ὑμᾶς εἰς πᾶσαν τὴν ἀλήθειαν οὐ γὰρ λαλήσει ἀφ᾽ ἑαυτοῦ ἀλλ᾽ ὅσα ἂν ἀκούσῃ λαλήσει καὶ τὰ ἐρχόμενα ἀναγγελεῖ ὑμῖν',
   'hotan de elthē ekeinos to pneuma tēs alētheias hodēgēsei hymas eis pasan tēn alētheian ou gar lalēsei aph heautou all hosa an akousē lalēsei kai ta erchomena ananggelei hymin',
   '''He will guide you into all truth'' (hodēgēsei hymas eis pasan tēn alētheian — will guide you into all the truth; hodēgeō: to lead as a guide on a journey, from hodos: road + agō: to lead). The Spirit is the Guide who leads into truth — not by replacing the disciples'' reasoning but by illuminating and directing it. ''He shall not speak of himself'' (ou lalēsei aph heautou — will not speak from himself) — the Spirit subordinates himself to Christ just as Christ subordinated himself to the Father (7:16-17; 14:10). ''Things to come'' (ta erchomena — the coming things) — prophetic revelation, particularly fulfilled in the book of Revelation.',
   NULL),
  (14, 'He shall glorify me: for he shall receive of mine, and shall shew it unto you.',
   'ἐκεῖνος ἐμὲ δοξάσει ὅτι ἐκ τοῦ ἐμοῦ λήψεται καὶ ἀναγγελεῖ ὑμῖν',
   'ekeinos eme doxasei hoti ek tou emou lēpsetai kai ananggelei hymin',
   '''He shall glorify me'' (ekeinos eme doxasei — that one will glorify me). The Spirit''s ministry is Christocentric: he glorifies Christ, not himself. Any spirit that glorifies itself or draws attention away from Christ is not the Holy Spirit (1 John 4:2-3). ''He shall receive of mine'' (ek tou emou lēpsetai — will receive from what is mine; taking from the treasure of Christ''s person and work) ''and shall shew it unto you'' (ananggelei hymin — will declare/announce it to you). The Spirit unpacks and applies the inexhaustible riches of Christ.',
   NULL),
  (15, 'All things that the Father hath are mine: therefore said I, that he shall take of mine, and shall shew it unto you.',
   'πάντα ὅσα ἔχει ὁ πατὴρ ἐμά ἐστιν διὰ τοῦτο εἶπον ὅτι ἐκ τοῦ ἐμοῦ λαμβάνει καὶ ἀναγγελεῖ ὑμῖν',
   'panta hosa echei ho patēr ema estin dia touto eipon hoti ek tou emou lambanei kai ananggelei hymin',
   '''All things that the Father hath are mine'' (panta hosa echei ho patēr ema estin — all things that the Father has are mine). The complete co-equality of Father and Son: what belongs to one belongs to the other. Therefore when the Spirit ''takes of mine,'' he is also taking of the Father''s. The Trinitarian unity is complete: the Father''s riches are the Son''s; the Son''s riches are what the Spirit reveals to the disciples. The believer receives the full inheritance of the triune God.',
   NULL),
  (16, 'A little while, and ye shall not see me: and again, a little while, and ye shall see me, because I go to the Father.',
   'μικρὸν καὶ οὐκέτι θεωρεῖτέ με καὶ πάλιν μικρὸν καὶ ὄψεσθέ με ὅτι ὑπάγω πρὸς τὸν πατέρα',
   'mikron kai ouketi theōreite me kai palin mikron kai opsesthe me hoti hypagō pros ton patera',
   '''A little while'' (mikron — a short time, a little; used twice). The first ''little while'' is the time between the Discourse and the crucifixion (hours). ''Ye shall not see me'' — the period of the burial and disciples'' absence from the cross. The second ''little while'' and ''ye shall see me'' likely refers to the resurrection appearances (the third day). The deeper meaning may also extend to the present age: believers do not see Jesus bodily, but will see him at his return (1 John 3:2).',
   NULL),
  (17, 'Then said some of his disciples among themselves, What is this that he saith unto us, A little while, and ye shall not see me: and again, a little while, and ye shall see me: and, Because I go to the Father?',
   'εἶπον οὖν ἐκ τῶν μαθητῶν αὐτοῦ πρὸς ἀλλήλους Τί ἐστιν τοῦτο ὃ λέγει ἡμῖν Μικρὸν καὶ οὐ θεωρεῖτέ με καὶ πάλιν μικρὸν καὶ ὄψεσθέ με καὶ ὅτι Ὑπάγω πρὸς τὸν πατέρα',
   'eipon oun ek tōn mathētōn autou pros allēlous Ti estin touto ho legei hēmin Mikron kai ou theōreite me kai palin mikron kai opsesthe me kai hoti Hypagō pros ton patera',
   'The disciples are genuinely bewildered — they discuss it among themselves rather than asking Jesus directly (perhaps fearing another answer they won''t understand). Jesus perceives their desire to ask and addresses it proactively (v.19). The repetition of his words in their question (verbatim) shows they have heard correctly but cannot interpret. Understanding comes from the Spirit (v.13), not merely from hearing.',
   NULL),
  (18, 'They said therefore, What is this that he saith, A little while? we cannot tell what he saith.',
   'ἔλεγον οὖν Τί ἐστιν τοῦτο ὃ λέγει τὸ μικρόν οὐκ οἴδαμεν τί λαλεῖ',
   'elegon oun Ti estin touto ho legei to mikron ouk oidamen ti lalei',
   '''We cannot tell what he saith'' (ouk oidamen ti lalei — we do not know what he is saying). Honest acknowledgement of incomprehension. The disciples'' confusion at this point (the night of the Last Supper) contrasts sharply with their post-resurrection understanding (Acts 2; the Epistles). The Spirit''s coming makes all the difference.',
   NULL),
  (19, 'Now Jesus knew that they were desirous to ask him, and said unto them, Do ye enquire among yourselves of that I said, A little while, and ye shall not see me: and again, a little while, and ye shall see me?',
   'ἔγνω ὁ Ἰησοῦς ὅτι ἤθελον αὐτὸν ἐρωτᾶν καὶ εἶπεν αὐτοῖς Περὶ τούτου ζητεῖτε μετ᾽ ἀλλήλων ὅτι εἶπον Μικρὸν καὶ οὐ θεωρεῖτέ με καὶ πάλιν μικρὸν καὶ ὄψεσθέ με',
   'egnō ho Iēsous hoti ēthelon auton erōtan kai eipen autois Peri toutou zēteite met allēlōn hoti eipon Mikron kai ou theōreite me kai palin mikron kai opsesthe me',
   '''Jesus knew that they were desirous to ask him'' (egnō ho Iēsous hoti ēthelon auton erōtan — Jesus knew that they wanted to ask him). Another demonstration of Jesus''s omniscience (cf. 1:47-48; 2:24-25; 6:64). He meets the question before it is fully formed. The pastoral care shown here — actively addressing the disciples'' confusion — is characteristic of the Good Shepherd.',
   NULL),
  (20, 'Verily, verily, I say unto you, That ye shall weep and lament, but the world shall rejoice: and ye shall be sorrowful, but your sorrow shall be turned into joy.',
   'ἀμὴν ἀμὴν λέγω ὑμῖν ὅτι κλαύσετε καὶ θρηνήσετε ὑμεῖς ὁ δὲ κόσμος χαρήσεται ὑμεῖς δὲ λυπηθήσεσθε ἀλλ᾽ ἡ λύπη ὑμῶν εἰς χαρὰν γενήσεται',
   'amēn amēn legō hymin hoti klausete kai thrēnēsete hymeis ho de kosmos charēsetai hymeis de lypēthēsesthe all hē lypē hymōn eis charan genēsetai',
   '''Ye shall weep and lament'' (klausete kai thrēnēsete — you will weep and wail; klaiō: to weep; thrēneō: to lament loudly, wail). ''The world shall rejoice'' — the crucifixion appeared to the world as victory over the troublemaker. ''Your sorrow shall be turned into joy'' (hē lypē hymōn eis charan genēsetai — your grief will become joy). Not merely that joy will follow sorrow, but that the very sorrow will be transformed into joy — the crucifixion becomes the resurrection, the worst thing becomes the best thing.',
   NULL),
  (21, 'A woman when she is in travail hath sorrow, because her hour is come: but as soon as she is delivered of the child, she remembereth no more the anguish, for joy that a man is born into the world.',
   'ἡ γυνὴ ὅταν τίκτῃ λύπην ἔχει ὅτι ἦλθεν ἡ ὥρα αὐτῆς ὅταν δὲ γεννήσῃ τὸ παιδίον οὐκέτι μνημονεύει τῆς θλίψεως διὰ τὴν χαρὰν ὅτι ἐγεννήθη ἄνθρωπος εἰς τὸν κόσμον',
   'hē gynē hotan tiktē lypēn echei hoti ēlthen hē hōra autēs hotan de gennēsē to paidion ouketi mnēmoneuei tēs thlipseōs dia tēn charan hoti egennēthē anthrōpos eis ton kosmon',
   '''She remembereth no more the anguish'' (ouketi mnēmoneuei tēs thlipseōs — she no longer remembers the tribulation). The birth analogy is profound: (1) the sorrow is real and intense; (2) the outcome transforms the experience retrospectively; (3) the new life that emerges is of infinitely greater value than the pain endured. The resurrection completely transforms the meaning of the crucifixion. Isaiah 66:7-8 and Micah 4:9-10 use the same imagery for the messianic deliverance.',
   NULL),
  (22, 'And ye now therefore have sorrow: but I will see you again, and your heart shall rejoice, and your joy no man taketh from you.',
   'καὶ ὑμεῖς οὖν νῦν μὲν λύπην ἔχετε πάλιν δὲ ὄψομαι ὑμᾶς καὶ χαρήσεται ὑμῶν ἡ καρδία καὶ τὴν χαρὰν ὑμῶν οὐδεὶς αἴρει ἀφ᾽ ὑμῶν',
   'kai hymeis oun nyn men lypēn echete palin de opsomai hymas kai charēsetai hymōn hē kardia kai tēn charan hymōn oudeis airei aph hymōn',
   '''Your joy no man taketh from you'' (tēn charan hymōn oudeis airei aph hymōn — your joy no one takes from you; present tense: no one is able to take it). The resurrection joy is permanent and unassailable. No persecution, bereavement, or tribulation can remove it because it is grounded not in circumstances but in the risen, living Christ (1 Peter 1:8: ''joy unspeakable and full of glory''). The world can take many things from the believer but not the inward joy of knowing the risen Lord.',
   NULL),
  (23, 'And in that day ye shall ask me nothing. Verily, verily, I say unto you, Whatsoever ye shall ask the Father in my name, he will give it you.',
   'καὶ ἐν ἐκείνῃ τῇ ἡμέρᾳ ἐμὲ οὐκ ἐρωτήσετε οὐδέν ἀμὴν ἀμὴν λέγω ὑμῖν ὅτι ὅσα ἂν αἰτήσητε τὸν πατέρα ἐν τῷ ὀνόματί μου δώσει ὑμῖν',
   'kai en ekeinē tē hēmera eme ouk erōtēsete ouden amēn amēn legō hymin hoti hosa an aitēsēte ton patera en tō onomati mou dōsei hymin',
   '''In that day ye shall ask me nothing'' (eme ouk erōtēsete ouden — you will ask me nothing; erōtaō: to ask a question, to enquire). In that day (after the resurrection, in the age of the Spirit) the disciples will no longer need to ask clarifying questions — the Spirit will guide them (v.13). The second clause introduces a different word for ''ask'': ''ask the Father'' (aitēsēte — ask, request, petition). Prayer to the Father in Christ''s name is the new mode of access in the post-resurrection age.',
   NULL),
  (24, 'Hitherto have ye asked nothing in my name: ask, and ye shall receive, that your joy may be full.',
   'ἕως ἄρτι οὐκ ᾐτήσατε οὐδὲν ἐν τῷ ὀνόματί μου αἰτεῖτε καὶ λήψεσθε ἵνα ἡ χαρὰ ὑμῶν ᾖ πεπληρωμένη',
   'heōs arti ouk ētēsate ouden en tō onomati mou aiteite kai lēpsesthe hina hē chara hymōn ē peplērōmenē',
   '''Hitherto have ye asked nothing in my name'' — prayer ''in the name of Jesus'' was not practiced during his earthly ministry; direct access through his name becomes available after his death, resurrection, and ascension. ''Ask, and ye shall receive, that your joy may be full'' (hina hē chara hymōn ē peplērōmenē — so that your joy may be filled up; perfect passive participle: completely, permanently filled). Answered prayer and fullness of joy are inseparably connected: prayer that is in alignment with Christ''s will and name will be answered, and answered prayer produces joy.',
   NULL),
  (25, 'These things have I spoken unto you in proverbs: but the time cometh, when I shall no more speak unto you in proverbs, but I shall shew you plainly of the Father.',
   'Ταῦτα ἐν παροιμίαις λελάληκα ὑμῖν ἔρχεται ὥρα ὅτε οὐκέτι ἐν παροιμίαις λαλήσω ὑμῖν ἀλλὰ παρρησίᾳ περὶ τοῦ πατρὸς ἀναγγελῶ ὑμῖν',
   'Tauta en paroimiais lelalēka hymin erchetai hōra hote ouketi en paroimiais lalēsō hymin alla parrēsia peri tou patros ananggelō hymin',
   '''In proverbs'' (en paroimiais — in figures, allegories, proverbial sayings; paroimia: a saying at the side of the road, a dark saying). The Upper Room Discourse has used many figurative expressions: ''going to the Father,'' ''the vine and branches,'' ''a little while.'' ''I shall shew you plainly'' (parrēsia — openly, boldly, without concealment; parrēsia: free-spokenness, frankness). After Pentecost, the apostles'' preaching and writings speak plainly about the Father''s nature, will, and purposes.',
   NULL),
  (26, 'At that day ye shall ask in my name: and I say not unto you, that I will pray the Father for you:',
   'ἐν ἐκείνῃ τῇ ἡμέρᾳ ἐν τῷ ὀνόματί μου αἰτήσεσθε καὶ οὐ λέγω ὑμῖν ὅτι ἐγὼ ἐρωτήσω τὸν πατέρα περὶ ὑμῶν',
   'en ekeinē tē hēmera en tō onomati mou aitēsesthe kai ou legō hymin hoti egō erōtēsō ton patera peri hymōn',
   '''I say not unto you, that I will pray the Father for you'' — this is not a denial of Christ''s intercession (cf. Romans 8:34; Hebrews 7:25; 1 John 2:1) but an emphasis on the directness of access believers now have to the Father. Christ''s intercession is not a separate prayer line that bypasses the Father; rather, prayer in Christ''s name brings the disciples directly into the Father''s presence. The mediation of Christ does not make the Father distant but accessible.',
   NULL),
  (27, 'For the Father himself loveth you, because ye have loved me, and have believed that I came out from God.',
   'αὐτὸς γὰρ ὁ πατὴρ φιλεῖ ὑμᾶς ὅτι ὑμεῖς ἐμὲ πεφιλήκατε καὶ πεπιστεύκατε ὅτι ἐγὼ παρὰ τοῦ θεοῦ ἐξῆλθον',
   'autos gar ho patēr philei hymas hoti hymeis eme pephilēkate kai pepisteukate hoti egō para tou theou exēlthon',
   '''The Father himself loveth you'' (autos ho patēr philei hymas — the Father himself loves you; philei from phileō: warm, personal affection). The disciples need not fear that God the Father is a cold, remote deity who must be appeased by the Son''s intercession. The Father himself is disposed toward the disciples in personal, warm love — the same ''friendly'' love that Jesus has for Lazarus (11:3,36). This love is because they have loved the Son and believed in his divine origin.',
   NULL),
  (28, 'I came forth from the Father, and am come into the world: again, I leave the world, and go to the Father.',
   'ἐξῆλθον παρὰ τοῦ πατρὸς καὶ ἐλήλυθα εἰς τὸν κόσμον πάλιν ἀφίημι τὸν κόσμον καὶ πορεύομαι πρὸς τὸν πατέρα',
   'exēlthon para tou patros kai elēlytha eis ton kosmon palin aphiēmi ton kosmon kai poreuomai pros ton patera',
   'Four movements in one verse: (1) ''I came forth from the Father'' — pre-existence and eternal origin; (2) ''am come into the world'' — the incarnation; (3) ''I leave the world'' — the ascension/departure; (4) ''go to the Father'' — return to the pre-incarnate glory. This is the entire arc of the Son''s mission in four clauses. It is perhaps the most compact summary of Johannine Christology in the Gospel. The disciples hear this and immediately understand — the plain speech Jesus promised (v.25) is already beginning.',
   NULL),
  (29, 'His disciples said unto him, Lo, now speakest thou plainly, and speakest no proverb.',
   'λέγουσιν αὐτῷ οἱ μαθηταὶ αὐτοῦ Ἴδε νῦν ἐν παρρησίᾳ λαλεῖς καὶ παροιμίαν οὐδεμίαν λέγεις',
   'legousin autō hoi mathētai autou Ide nyn en parrēsia laleis kai paroimian oudemian legeis',
   '''Lo, now speakest thou plainly'' (Ide, nyn en parrēsia laleis — look, now you speak openly). The disciples feel they have finally understood — and they have grasped more than before. But the test of understanding will come in Gethsemane and at the cross, where their apparent comprehension will be overwhelmed by events. Understanding Christ''s words about the cross is always partial until you have been through it.',
   NULL),
  (30, 'Now are we sure that thou knowest all things, and needest not that any man should ask thee: by this we believe that thou camest forth from God.',
   'νῦν οἴδαμεν ὅτι οἶδας πάντα καὶ οὐ χρείαν ἔχεις ἵνα τίς σε ἐρωτᾷ ἐν τούτῳ πιστεύομεν ὅτι ἀπὸ θεοῦ ἐξῆλθες',
   'nyn oidamen hoti oidas panta kai ou chreian echeis hina tis se erōtā en toutō pisteuomen hoti apo theou exēlthes',
   '''Thou knowest all things'' (oidas panta — you know all things). They base their confidence on his foreknowledge — he knew their questions before they asked (v.19). ''By this we believe that thou camest forth from God'' — the confession is genuine but premature in its confidence. Jesus immediately tests it (v.31).',
   NULL),
  (31, 'Jesus answered them, Do ye now believe?',
   'ἀπεκρίθη αὐτοῖς Ἰησοῦς Ἄρτι πιστεύετε',
   'apekrithē autois Iēsous Arti pisteuete',
   '''Do ye now believe?'' (Arti pisteuete — Do you believe now?). This can be read as a gentle question or an affirmation with an implied contrast: ''you believe now — but watch what is about to happen to your faith.'' The disciples'' faith is real but shallow-rooted; the storm that is coming will prove its depth. Jesus does not dismiss their faith but warns that it will be severely tested.',
   NULL),
  (32, 'Behold, the hour cometh, yea, is now come, that ye shall be scattered, every man to his own, and shall leave me alone: and yet I am not alone, because the Father is with me.',
   'ἰδοὺ ἔρχεται ὥρα καὶ νῦν ἐλήλυθεν ἵνα σκορπισθῆτε ἕκαστος εἰς τὰ ἴδια κἀμὲ μόνον ἀφῆτε καὶ οὐκ εἰμὶ μόνος ὅτι ὁ πατὴρ μετ᾽ ἐμοῦ ἐστιν',
   'idou erchetai hōra kai nyn elēlythen hina skorpisthēte hekastos eis ta idia kame monon aphēte kai ouk eimi monos hoti ho patēr met emou estin',
   '''Scattered every man to his own'' (skorpisthēte hekastos eis ta idia — you will be scattered, each one to his own things; fulfilling Zechariah 13:7: ''smite the shepherd, and the sheep shall be scattered''). ''Leave me alone'' (kame monon aphēte — and leave me alone). The disciples'' scattering is predicted with perfect accuracy — fulfilled in Gethsemane (Matthew 26:56; Mark 14:50). But: ''I am not alone, because the Father is with me'' (ouk eimi monos hoti ho patēr met emou estin). Even in his worst moment of human abandonment, the Father is present. The cry of dereliction (Matthew 27:46) is the one moment of abandonment — even from the Father — that Jesus will bear for us.',
   NULL),
  (33, 'These things I have spoken unto you, that in me ye might have peace. In the world ye shall have tribulation: but be of good cheer; I have overcome the world.',
   'ταῦτα λελάληκα ὑμῖν ἵνα ἐν ἐμοὶ εἰρήνην ἔχητε ἐν τῷ κόσμῳ θλῖψιν ἔξετε ἀλλὰ θαρσεῖτε ἐγὼ νενίκηκα τὸν κόσμον',
   'tauta lelalēka hymin hina en emoi eirēnēn echēte en tō kosmō thlipsin exete alla tharseite egō nenikēka ton kosmon',
   '''In the world ye shall have tribulation'' (en tō kosmō thlipsin exete — in the world you will have tribulation; thlipsis: pressure, distress, affliction — from thlibō: to press, squeeze). This is not a warning but a statement of guaranteed fact. ''But be of good cheer'' (alla tharseite — but take courage, be bold; tharseo: to be courageous). The courage is grounded in a completed act: ''I have overcome the world'' (egō nenikēka ton kosmon — I have overcome the world; perfect tense: a past victory with permanent standing). The cross was the victory, though it appeared defeat. ''Nenikēka'' (from nikaō: to conquer, overcome). The same root as the ''overcomers'' of Revelation (2:7,11,17,26; 3:5,12,21; 21:7). Believers overcome because Christ has already overcome (1 John 5:4-5; Romans 8:37).',
   NULL)
) AS v(verse_number, kjv_text, original_text, transliteration, study_note, doctrinal_note)
WHERE b.name = 'John' AND c.chapter_number = 16;

-- JOHN CHAPTER 16 — BACKFILL (word_studies + cross_references)

INSERT INTO word_studies (verse_id, original_word, transliteration, strongs_number, meaning, word_order)
SELECT v.id, w.original_word, w.transliteration, w.strongs_number, w.meaning, w.word_order
FROM verses v JOIN chapters c ON v.chapter_id = c.id
JOIN books b ON c.book_id = b.id
CROSS JOIN (VALUES
  (1, 'ἵνα μὴ σκανδαλισθῆτε', 'hina mē skandalisthēte', 'G4624', 'That ye should not be offended — skandalizō = to cause to stumble, trap. Jesus forewarns so that coming persecution does not shipwreck faith; prophecy is pastoral prophylaxis.', 1),
  (2, 'ἀποσυναγώγους ποιήσουσιν ὑμᾶς', 'aposynagōgous poiēsousin hymas', 'G656/G4160', 'Put you out of the synagogues — aposynagōgos (John''s word: 9:22; 12:42). Excommunication cut off social, economic, and religious standing. The new community will face the old community''s ban.', 2),
  (2, 'λατρείαν προσφέρειν τῷ Θεῷ', 'latreian prospherein tō Theō', 'G2999/G4374', 'Doeth God service — latreia = cultic/priestly service. Persecutors will kill Christians thinking they offer worship to God — a chilling anticipation of Saul of Tarsus and every religiously-rationalised martyrdom.', 3),
  (4, 'ἀρχῆς', 'archēs', 'G746', 'From the beginning — Jesus has withheld these warnings until now because, while present, he absorbed the persecution himself. Now that he departs, the disciples step into the crosshairs; preparation becomes urgent.', 4),
  (5, 'οὐδεὶς ἐξ ὑμῶν ἐρωτᾷ με', 'oudeis ex hymōn erōta me', 'G3762/G2065', 'None of you asketh me — despite Peter''s ''whither'' in 13:36 and Thomas''s in 14:5, they have stopped pursuing the question. Grief has paralysed curiosity; they should be asking about destination, not only departure.', 5),
  (6, 'λύπη πεπλήρωκεν τὴν καρδίαν', 'lypē peplērōken tēn kardian', 'G3077/G4137', 'Sorrow hath filled your heart — lypē = grief. The disciples focus on loss rather than gain; Jesus will turn the grief inside out in v.20-22.', 6),
  (7, 'συμφέρει ὑμῖν ἵνα ἐγὼ ἀπέλθω', 'sympherei hymin hina egō apelthō', 'G4851/G565', 'Expedient for you that I go away — sympherei = it is profitable/to advantage. The incarnation''s localised presence yields, in exchange for the Spirit''s universal indwelling. A staggering theology of ascension: Jesus withdrawn to the throne is more accessible than Jesus confined to Galilee.', 7),
  (7, 'πέμψω αὐτὸν πρὸς ὑμᾶς', 'pempsō auton pros hymas', 'G3992', 'I will send him unto you — the Son sends the Spirit (cf. 15:26). Trinitarian missio: Father and Son co-sending.', 8),
  (8, 'ἐλέγξει τὸν κόσμον', 'elegxei ton kosmon', 'G1651/G2889', 'Reprove the world — elegchō = to convict, expose, bring to conviction (both forensic and moral). The Spirit''s convicting work is prosecutorial: he brings the world into court and exposes its case as false.', 9),
  (8, 'περὶ ἁμαρτίας καὶ περὶ δικαιοσύνης καὶ περὶ κρίσεως', 'peri hamartias kai peri dikaiosynēs kai peri kriseōs', 'G266/G1343/G2920', 'Of sin, righteousness, judgment — the threefold conviction: sin defined by unbelief in Christ (v.9); righteousness defined by Christ''s vindicating return to the Father (v.10); judgment defined by Satan''s defeat (v.11). A Christocentric apologetic by the Spirit.', 10),
  (10, 'οὐκέτι θεωρεῖτέ με', 'ouketi theōreite me', 'G3765/G2334', 'Ye see me no more — theōreō = to observe with the eyes. The ascension removes physical sight; the next seeing is eschatological (1 John 3:2).', 11),
  (11, 'ὁ ἄρχων τοῦ κόσμου τούτου κέκριται', 'ho archōn tou kosmou toutou kekritai', 'G758/G2889/G2919', 'Prince of this world is judged — perfect passive: has been judged and stands condemned. At the cross, Satan''s verdict was entered; his ongoing activity is appeal-without-reversal.', 12),
  (12, 'οὐ δύνασθε βαστάζειν ἄρτι', 'ou dynasthe bastazein arti', 'G941/G737', 'Ye cannot bear them now — bastazō = to carry, endure. Pedagogical restraint: revelation is paced to capacity. Post-Pentecost they will bear more.', 13),
  (13, 'τὸ Πνεῦμα τῆς ἀληθείας... ὁδηγήσει', 'to Pneuma tēs alētheias... hodēgēsei', 'G4151/G225/G3594', 'Spirit of truth... will guide — hodēgeō = to lead the way (literally ''way-lead'', cf. hodos). The Spirit guides into all truth — comprehensive but Christ-centred, not novel revelation detached from Jesus.', 14),
  (13, 'τὰ ἐρχόμενα ἀναγγελεῖ', 'ta erchomena anangelei', 'G2064/G312', 'Show you things to come — anangellō = to announce. Covers both apostolic prophecy and the eschatological content of the New Testament (esp. Revelation).', 15),
  (14, 'ἐκεῖνος ἐμὲ δοξάσει', 'ekeinos eme doxasei', 'G1392', 'He shall glorify me — the Spirit''s mission is Christ-glorifying, not self-promoting. Any ''spirit'' that deflects from Jesus is not the Holy Spirit.', 16),
  (14, 'ἐκ τοῦ ἐμοῦ λήμψεται', 'ek tou emou lēmpsetai', 'G2983', 'Shall take of mine — the Spirit mediates the riches of Christ to the church. Nothing the Spirit reveals originates apart from Christ; everything belongs to him and is passed on to us (v.15).', 17),
  (16, 'μικρὸν καὶ οὐκέτι θεωρεῖτέ με', 'mikron kai ouketi theōreite me', 'G3398/G2334', 'A little while and ye shall not see me — the two mikra: first absence (cross/burial), second presence (resurrection), with further sense of ascension-until-Parousia. Deliberate ambiguity layered with multiple horizons.', 18),
  (20, 'θρηνήσετε... κόσμος χαρήσεται', 'thrēnēsete... kosmos charēsetai', 'G2354/G5463', 'Ye shall weep and lament... the world shall rejoice — thrēneō = to wail a dirge. At the cross the lamentation and rejoicing invert; at the resurrection they invert again, permanently.', 19),
  (20, 'ἡ λύπη ὑμῶν εἰς χαρὰν γενήσεται', 'hē lypē hymōn eis charan genēsetai', 'G3077/G5479/G1096', 'Your sorrow shall be turned into joy — not replaced, but transformed. The very wound becomes the source of joy (the scars are present yet no longer painful, 20:20, 27).', 20),
  (21, 'ἡ γυνὴ ὅταν τίκτῃ', 'hē gynē hotan tiktē', 'G1135/G5088', 'Woman in travail — childbirth analogy: severe pain giving way to joy that eclipses the pain. Old Testament background of Zion''s birth-pangs for the messianic age (Isa 26:17; 66:7-9; Mic 5:3).', 21),
  (23, 'ἐν ἐκείνῃ τῇ ἡμέρᾳ', 'en ekeinē tē hēmera', 'G2250', 'In that day — the post-resurrection era, opened by Easter and confirmed at Pentecost. Direct access to the Father without the earthly Jesus as intermediary.', 22),
  (23, 'αἰτήσητε τὸν πατέρα ἐν τῷ ὀνόματί μου', 'aitēsēte ton patera en tō onomati mou', 'G154/G3962/G3686', 'Ask the Father in my name — prayer addressed to the Father through the Son''s mediation. New-covenant access formula, made operational by the finished work of Christ.', 23),
  (24, 'ἵνα ἡ χαρὰ ὑμῶν ᾖ πεπληρωμένη', 'hina hē chara hymōn ē peplērōmenē', 'G5479/G4137', 'That your joy may be full — perfect passive participle: joy brought to completed fulness. Prayer in Jesus'' name is a divinely ordained channel of saturated joy.', 24),
  (25, 'ἐν παροιμίαις... παρρησίᾳ', 'en paroimiais... parrēsia', 'G3942/G3954', 'In proverbs... plainly — paroimia = figurative speech, dark saying (cf. parabolē). parrēsia = frank, bold, open speech. The post-Pentecost era will know unambiguous revelation; the current veiling gives way to clarity.', 25),
  (27, 'αὐτὸς ὁ πατὴρ φιλεῖ ὑμᾶς', 'autos ho patēr philei hymas', 'G3962/G5368', 'The Father himself loveth you — phileō (warm, affectionate love). The disciples'' love for Jesus meets with the Father''s own warm reciprocity; the circuit of love completes.', 26),
  (28, 'ἐξῆλθον παρὰ τοῦ πατρός', 'exēlthon para tou patros', 'G1831/G3962', 'I came forth from the Father — the four-fold career: from the Father, into the world, leaving the world, returning to the Father. A compact Johannine Christology of incarnation and exaltation.', 27),
  (29, 'παρρησίᾳ λαλεῖς', 'parrēsia laleis', 'G3954/G2980', 'Now speakest thou plainly — the disciples perceive a shift to clarity, though Jesus rebuts their confidence in v.31-32: their grasp is partial; full comprehension awaits Pentecost.', 28),
  (32, 'σκορπισθῆτε ἕκαστος εἰς τὰ ἴδια', 'skorpisthēte hekastos eis ta idia', 'G4650/G2398', 'Ye shall be scattered — fulfilment of Zech 13:7 (''smite the shepherd and the sheep shall be scattered''), quoted in Matt 26:31. Each flees to ''his own'' (personal safety); the ecclesial body disintegrates in Gethsemane.', 29),
  (32, 'ὁ πατὴρ μετ᾽ ἐμοῦ ἐστιν', 'ho patēr met emou estin', 'G3962', 'The Father is with me — the conscious filial intimacy sustaining Jesus through abandonment by disciples. Not inconsistent with the dereliction cry (Matt 27:46); that later moment reflects the uniquely borne wrath, not a rupture of essential union.', 30),
  (33, 'ἐν ἐμοὶ εἰρήνην ἔχητε', 'en emoi eirēnēn echēte', 'G1722/G1515', 'In me ye might have peace — the locus of eirēnē is en emoi, in union with Christ. Outside him is the world''s thlipsis; inside him, the Father''s peace.', 31),
  (33, 'θλῖψιν ἔξετε', 'thlipsin exete', 'G2347', 'Ye shall have tribulation — thlipsis = pressure, squeezing (from thlibō, to crush grapes). Persecution is promised, not possible. The Christian life includes guaranteed pressure in the world system.', 32),
  (33, 'ἐγὼ νενίκηκα τὸν κόσμον', 'egō nenikēka ton kosmon', 'G3528/G2889', 'I have overcome the world — perfect active: definitive, permanent victory. nikaō = to conquer (root of the Nicene ''overcomer'' theology, Rev 2-3; 1 John 5:4-5). Spoken before the cross; the victory is certain in the Father''s counsel.', 33),
  (9, 'περὶ ἁμαρτίας ὅτι οὐ πιστεύουσιν', 'peri hamartias hoti ou pisteuousin', 'G266/G4100', 'Of sin, because they believe not — the definitive sin is unbelief in Christ. All other sins stem from this root rupture with the sent Son.', 34),
  (10, 'περὶ δικαιοσύνης ὅτι πρὸς τὸν πατέρα ὑπάγω', 'peri dikaiosynēs hoti pros ton patera hypagō', 'G1343/G3962/G5217', 'Of righteousness, because I go to my Father — Christ''s ascension is the Father''s vindicating verdict. The one the world condemned, the Father enthroned.', 35)
) AS w(verse_number, original_word, transliteration, strongs_number, meaning, word_order)
WHERE b.name = 'John' AND c.chapter_number = 16 AND v.verse_number = w.verse_number
ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;

